item.ns1:encoded:

Bogotá saw fresh anti-US protests as Colombians rejected Washington’s escalating aggression in Latin America. [comra] reporters were on the ground as protests erupted after the US invaded Venezuela and kidnapped President Nicolás Maduro, sparking broad anger over US imperialism. Protesters burned US flags and Trump effigies on Bogotá’s streets, expressing solidarity with Cuba, Venezuela, and Palestine. Tensions between Colombia’s President Gustavo Petro and US President Donald Trump have been rising amid US military threats and aggressive rhetoric. Trump openly threatened military action against Colombia after the Venezuela invasion, deepening anti-US sentiment among grassroots groups. Despite a phone call that eased immediate diplomatic tensions, protests continued in Bogotá and other cities. Colombians mobilised beyond official channels, driven by fear of foreign intervention and a demand that Washington respect national sovereignty.
